# Block Architecture Audit

A bug exists anywhere a feature is **declared** in `block.json` or **visible** in `edit.js` but never makes it through to `save.js → database → render.php`.

## 1. Inner blocks must be serialized

If the block uses `replaceInnerBlocks` or `<InnerBlocks>` in `edit.js`, `save.js` **must** return `<InnerBlocks.Content />` (not `null`). Returning `null` silently discards inner blocks on every save — they exist in the editor's in-memory state but are never written to the database, so `render.php` always receives `$content = ''`.

```js
// BAD — inner blocks are lost on save
export default function save() { return null; }

// GOOD
export default function save() { return <InnerBlocks.Content />; }
```

When changing from `null` to `<InnerBlocks.Content />`, add a deprecation entry so existing posts auto-recover.

## 2. render.php must call `get_block_wrapper_attributes()`

Without this call, every block support the user configures in the editor — `spacing.margin`, `spacing.padding`, `color.background`, `border.*`, `shadow`, `dimensions.minHeight` — is silently discarded on the frontend.

```php
// BAD — supports are ignored on the frontend
printf( '<div class="aldus-layout">%s</div>', $content );

// GOOD — supports applied; wp-block-{name} class added automatically
printf(
    '<div %s>%s</div>',
    get_block_wrapper_attributes( [ 'class' => 'aldus-layout' ] ),
    $content
);
```

## 3. render.php early exits must use printf/echo, not return

WordPress includes `render.php` via `ob_start()`/`ob_get_clean()`. A `return` value is discarded; only printed output is captured.

```php
// BAD — message is silently dropped
if ( $empty ) { return sprintf( '<div>%s</div>', $msg ); }

// GOOD
if ( $empty ) { printf( '<div>%s</div>', $msg ); return; }
```

## 4. selectors.root must match the actual root element class

If `block.json` has `"selectors": { "root": ".wp-block-foo" }` but `render.php` outputs `<div class="foo-wrapper">`, block-level CSS selectors will miss the element. Use `get_block_wrapper_attributes()` — it adds `wp-block-{name}` automatically, keeping selectors in sync.

## 5. providesContext keys must be consumed

Every key in `providesContext` must have at least one inner block with a matching `usesContext` entry. Unused context keys waste a read on every block render. Remove them or annotate them as planned future features.

## 6. Block supports audit

For each `supports` entry in `block.json`, confirm it is wired in **both** directions:
- **PHP (frontend):** `get_block_wrapper_attributes()` in `render.php`
- **JS (editor save):** `useBlockProps.save()` in `save.js` (if the block has a static wrapper)
